1. This project is created using reactjs framework.

2. This project is only frontend side of photo-editor  for designing photo book, calendar, acrylic prints, canvas print, photo prints and  photo items.

3. Our  main component is @src/layout/index.jsx which is used to render the main layout of the editor.

4. Dont change or modify folder structure.

5. All the common-components are stored in @src/common-components folder and subfolder.

6. All the design-components are stored in @src/components folder and subfolder (e.g., text, sticker ,photo,shape,canvas,dynamic calendar etc) which is helping us to deign in the canvas.

7. Our  main  designing component is stored in @src/components/canvas/Canvas.jsx which is used to render the canvas and all the design on it.

8. All the popups are stored in @src/components/popups folder (e.g., editorSettings, sizeSettings,objectProperties etc).

9. Our main layout components are stored in @src/layout folder (e.g., header,footer,sidebar, topActions,bottomActions etc). 

10. All canvas components (e.g, photo,sticker,shape) which are used in  any product preview are stored in @src/layout/preview folder.

11. All the tools are stored in @src/tools folder and subfolder (e.g., photos, layouts, background, stickers, text, frames, masks etc) with its related components.

12. All the 2D or 3D Priview components of products are stored in @src/products-preview folder and subfolder (e.g., photobook, canvas print, acrylic print).

13. All the assets are stored in @src/assets folder and subfolder (e.g., images,icons,svg, videos etc).

14. All the styled components and global style classes are stored in @src/common-components/StyledComponents.jsx.

15. All the utils are stored in @src/library/utils folder and subfolder.

16. All  the redux slices are stored in @src/store/slices/ folder

17. Our main store configuration is stored in @src/store/store.jsx.

18. All .glb files for 3D preview are stored in @public/3d folder.

19. canvasSliceGetter are stored in @src/library/utils/helpers/canvasSliceGetters.js.

20. All the common functions are stored in @src/library/utils/common-functions  folder.

21. All the common services are stored in @src/library/utils/common-services folder.

22. All the constants are stored in @src/library/utils/constants folder.

23. All the custom hooks are stored in @src/library/utils/custom-hooks folder.

24. All  the jsons are stored in @src/library/utils/jsons folder.

25. All the threejs related functions are stored in @src/library/utils/three-js-functions folder.

26. Use functional and declarative programming patterns; avoid classes.

27. Use descriptive variable names with auxiliary verbs (e.g., isLoading, hasError)

28. Naming Conventions
    -Use lowercase with dashes for directories (e.g., components/canvas)
    -Favor named exports for components and utilities
    -Use PascalCase for component files (e.g., Canvas.jsx)
    -Use camelCase for utility files (e.g., canvasSliceGetters.js)
29. Use javascript  for all components and utilities with latest ES syntax and best practices.  

30.  Syntax and Formatting:
    -Use "function" keyword for pure functions
    -Avoid unnecessary curly braces in conditionals
    -Use declarative JSX
31.  UI and Styling:
    - All components should be modern and responsive
    -Use Bootstrap for styling with its prebuilt components and grid system to create responsive UI.
    -use `npm install react-bootstrap bootstrap` to install it globally (this is already done).
    -use react-icons for icons

32.  Error Handling:
    -Implement proper error boundaries
    -Log errors appropriately for debugging
    -Provide user-friendly error messages
    -Handle network failures gracefully

33. Security:
 -Sanitize user input
 -Handle sensitive data carefully

34. Performance Optimizations:
  -Optimize code for maximum speed
  -Use memoization where possible

35. Code Reuse and Modularization:
  -Reuse components and functions where possible
  -Create reusable components and functions using functional and declarative programming patterns
  -Use redux for state management
  -Use redux-thunk for async actions

36. Accessibility:
  -Implement accessibility best practices
  -Use aria-label and aria-labelledby attributes where necessary
  -Use alt attribute for images
  -Use keyboard navigation for accessibility

37. Git Usage:  
    Commit Message Prefixes:
     -"fix:" for bug fixes
     -"feat:" for new features
     -"perf:" for performance improvements
     -"docs:" for documentation changes
     -"style:" for formatting changes
     -"refactor:" for code refactoring
     -"test:" for adding missing tests
     -"chore:" for maintenance tasks
     -"build:" for changes that affect the build system or external dependencies
    Commit Rules:
        -Use lowercase for commit messages
        -Keep the summary line concise
        -Include description for non-obvious changes
        -Reference issue numbers when applicable
   -always create a new branch for each feature or bug fix
   -always push the changes to the remote repository before making a pull request

38. Code Quality:
    -Follow coding conventions and best practices
    -Use consistent naming conventions
    -Use consistent indentation and spacing
    -Use comments to explain code logic
    -Use linting and formatting tools
    
39. API Calls:
    -always use  utilities functions for api calls which defined in @src/library/utils/common-services/apiCall.js (e.g., apiPost, apiGet)
    -must use try catch block while making api calls
    -always use  defined endpoints for api calls which defined in @src/library/utils/constants/apiurl.js
    -handle errors from api calls with appropriate messages

